Messy Charisma

Dissolve the Nemesis

When used for cleaning, soap solubilizes particles and grime, which can then be separated from the object being cleaned. In hand washing, as a surfactant, when lathered with a little water, soap kills microorganisms such as bacteria and viruses by disorganizing their membrane layer and denaturing their proteins. It also emulsifies oils, enabling them to be carried away by running water.

Lipophilic interior

Meet the Micelle

The micelle is a cell-like structure formed by the aggregation of the soap compounds. The exterior of the micelle is hydrophilic (attracted to water) and the interior is lipophilic (attracted to oils).

The insoluble oil/fat molecules become associated inside micelles, tiny spheres formed from soap molecules with polar hydrophilic (water-attracting) groups on the outside and encasing a lipophilic (fat-attracting) pocket, which shields the oil/fat molecules from the water making it soluble. Anything that is soluble will be washed away with the water.
